XVII. Antium, June, 56 B.c.

1. perbelle: upon per in corn- pounds, cf. Intr. 77. Bellefacis‚ bene sacis, etc.‚ are colloquial phrases to express gratitude. Cf. bene bem‘g- neque arbitror te fizcere, Plaut. Most. 816; bene hercle factum et habeo vobis gratiam, Rud. 83 5.— Tyranniofiis: a grammarian and teacher who was brought to Rome as a prisoner by L. Lucullus. He was at one time tutor of the young Cicero. His services in arranging Cicero’s books are mentioned in Att. 4. 8 Α; Q. fr. 3. 4. 5, and Ep. XXIII. 6 also. The place in which this letter was written is deter- mined by comparing it with Att. 4. 8 Α.- tuis librariolis: cf. Intr. 58. Some of Cicero‘s works were probably published by Atticus3 cf.
